### 6.2 Fault Distribution by Inverter

| Inverter | FAULT | MAINT | COMM_FAIL | Total Non-Normal |
|----------|-------|-------|-----------|-----------------|
| INV-01 | 40 | 30 | 27 | 97 |
| INV-07 | 37 | 41 | 17 | 95 |
| INV-05 | 37 | 34 | 24 | 95 |
| INV-03 | 39 | 29 | 21 | 89 |
| INV-02 | 36 | 29 | 24 | 89 |
| INV-06 | 36 | 35 | 16 | 87 |
| INV-04 | 34 | 27 | 30 | 91 |
| INV-08 | 34 | 20 | 21 | 75 |

No single inverter dominates the fault count. The distribution is close to uniform (34–40 faults each), suggesting fleet-wide rather than asset-specific triggers.

### 6.3 Fault Duration Analysis

| Statistic | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Median duration | 30 minutes |
| Mean duration | 30.3 minutes |
| Maximum observed | 60 minutes |
| Total fault events | 290 |

The median fault duration of exactly 30 minutes — which equals precisely one SCADA reporting interval — is highly diagnostic. This pattern is characteristic of **auto-recovery events**: the system logs a fault state and then self-clears before the next poll. It strongly suggests communication timeouts, soft resets, or SCADA polling failures rather than hardware failures.

### 6.4 Temporal Distribution of Faults

Faults are distributed across all 24 hours with no significant clustering at any particular time of day. This is the opposite of what would be expected from thermally-driven faults (which would peak in afternoon hours) or irradiance-related events. Combined with the 30-minute auto-recovery pattern, this further supports a **communication or logging artefact** interpretation.

### 6.5 Pre-Fault Conditions

Average DC power in the three readings preceding a FAULT event: **760 kW**. This is consistent with normal mid-generation operation, providing no evidence that overload conditions precede faults.

