## 9. Recommendations & Next Steps

### Priority 1 — Immediate (within 1 week)

**INV-03 physical inspection**
Schedule a string-level IV curve trace and visual inspection of all panels connected to INV-03. The 26% intra-period output decline is consistent with: progressive soiling across a string, partial shading from a new obstruction, a failing bypass diode, or a loose/corroded DC string connection. The fact that inverter efficiency is unaffected (97.0%) confirms the fault is upstream of the inverter.

**Fix INV-05 dc_power_kw unit bug**
Divide all `dc_power_kw` values for INV-05 by 1,000 at the data pipeline source. Verify against AC output readings after the fix.

### Priority 2 — Short-term (within 1 month)

**INV-01 investigation**
INV-01 has been consistently 9.6% below fleet average for the entire 90-day period. Unlike INV-03, it shows no worsening trend, suggesting a persistent rather than progressive issue — possibly a partial string outage, module soiling on one sub-array, or a misconfigured MPPT channel.

**Weather data temperature normalisation**
Resolve the mixed °C/°F issue at source. Investigate why all three stations report identical mean temperatures — this may indicate a data averaging or interpolation issue in the weather station logger.

### Priority 3 — Pipeline improvements

**Sentinel value handling** — Replace -9999 values with NULL at ingestion rather than relying on downstream clipping.

**Timestamp standardisation** — Enforce a single ISO 8601 timestamp format in `inverter_scada.csv` at the SCADA system level.

**Fault-weather correlation** — Cross-reference COMM_FAIL and FAULT events with precipitation and wind speed data to determine if environmental conditions are a contributing factor.

**Automated underperformance alerting** — Implement a weekly rolling comparison of inverter output against fleet average; trigger an alert when any inverter deviates by more than 10% for two consecutive weeks.

